        var COMMENTARY_DATA = {
            // ── GENESIS ────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Genesis': {
                bishops_book:  'Genesis is the seed of the entire Bible — pull on any thread in Revelation and it leads back here. From creation to covenant, God\'s sovereign purpose unfolds through flawed, faith-filled people. Every pastor needs this book. It answers the questions your congregation carries into the pew: Where did we come from? Why is the world broken? Is there any hope? Genesis says yes — emphatically.',
                matthew_book:  'Genesis, the book of beginnings, is rightly placed first in the canon of Scripture, for in it we find the origin of all things — the creation of the universe, the nature of man made in God\'s image, the tragedy of the Fall, and the dawn of redemptive promise. Here God speaks and worlds come into being; here God promises and covenants that will reshape human history are established.',
                jamieson_book: 'Genesis (from the Greek genesis, "beginning") covers the period from creation to the death of Joseph, approximately 2300 years of history. The authorship of Moses is attested by Christ himself (John 5:46). The book divides naturally at chapter 12: primeval history (1-11) and patriarchal history (12-50). The toledoth formula ("these are the generations of") provides its structural key.',
                chapters: {
                    '1': {
                        bishops:  'Genesis 1 is not a science textbook — it is a theological manifesto. Ten times we read "God said," and ten times it was so. Before you preach on creation, understand what Moses is doing: he is demolishing the rival gods of Egypt and Babylon. The sun is not a deity — it is a lamp God hung in the sky. The ocean is not chaos — it is waters God gathered. Preach this chapter as the declaration that our God reigns over everything that terrifies other nations. The takeaway for your congregation: the same God who spoke light into primordial darkness is speaking into the dark places of their lives right now.',
                        matthew:  'In the beginning God created — these five words contain the whole of natural theology. First, they establish the existence and eternality of God, who precedes all things. Second, they assert creation ex nihilo: God made heaven and earth out of nothing, by the word of His power. Observe the Spirit of God moving upon the face of the waters — the same Spirit who would later brood over the spiritual chaos of fallen humanity to bring the new creation. The six days of creation culminate in the Sabbath, which is not merely a rest from labor but a participation in divine delight over a completed and good work.',
                        jamieson: 'The opening verse (v.1) functions as a summary statement, with verses 2-31 providing the narrative detail. The Hebrew bara (create) is used exclusively of divine creation and carries no connotation of pre-existing material. The construct "formless and void" (tohu wabohu) describes not a rival chaotic power but a state of raw, unordered potential awaiting divine ordering. The sequential days (yom with ordinal numbers) have been interpreted as literal days, days of revelation to Moses, or literary frameworks — the exegete must weigh the hermeneutical options carefully.'
                    },
                    '3': {
                        bishops:  'Genesis 3 is the hinge of all human history, and the passage every honest preacher must return to again and again. The Serpent\'s strategy is identical today: "Did God really say?" Before you can help people resist temptation, you must help them see how the enemy works — he questions God\'s word, then contradicts it, then offers a counterfeit. Notice Eve\'s progression: she saw, she desired, she took, she gave. Sin always follows that sequence. But here is the miracle hidden in judgment: verse 15. In the curse on the Serpent, God announces the gospel. The seed of the woman will crush his head. Preach Genesis 3 and you\'re preaching the cross.',
                        matthew:  'Chapter 3 records the most catastrophic event in human history, the consequences of which extend to every page of Scripture thereafter. Observe how the tempter begins not with outright denial but with the subtle interrogative: "Did God actually say?" Doubt precedes disobedience. When Eve added to God\'s word ("neither shall you touch it") she revealed a heart already inclining toward suspicion of divine goodness. Adam stood silently beside her — his passive failure is as culpable as her active transgression. Yet God\'s first question after the Fall is "Where are you?" — not an inquiry of ignorance, but the first call of grace, which has echoed through every generation since.',
                        jamieson: 'The identification of the Serpent with Satan is confirmed by Revelation 12:9 and 20:2. The tree of the knowledge of good and evil represented the boundary of creaturely existence — the sphere God reserved for Himself. The Hebrew nakhas (serpent) was a real animal used as an instrument; Genesis 3:1 describes it as "more crafty than any other beast," pointing to an external agency. The protoevangelium (v.15) — enmity between seed of woman and seed of serpent — is the first messianic prophecy; the bruising of the heel (Christ\'s suffering) and the crushing of the head (Satan\'s destruction) are fulfilled at Calvary and the Parousia.'
                    },
                    '12': {
                        bishops:  'Genesis 12 is one of the most important chapters in the entire Bible because everything God does from here to Revelation flows through this covenant. God calls Abram — a pagan from Ur — and says, "Go." No explanation, no map, no guarantee except My word. This is faith in its purest form. Notice the structure of the call: first God blesses Abram (five "I will" statements), then He commissions him ("be a blessing"), then He promises global reach ("all families of the earth shall be blessed"). That\'s your sermon structure right there. God fills us so we can overflow to others. And that blessing becomes Jesus — the seed of Abraham in whom all nations find redemption.',
                        matthew:  'The call of Abram in chapter 12 is the pivot of redemptive history. The cursings of chapter 3 and the confusion of Babel in chapter 11 give way to the divine blessing channeled through one man whose posterity would ultimately bless all nations. Note the threefold promise: land, seed, and blessing — themes that will be progressively developed through the patriarchal narratives and find their ultimate fulfillment in Christ. "Get out of your country" — God\'s call invariably involves separation from what is familiar to embrace what is promised. Abram\'s obedience, though imperfect, is the pattern of all saving faith.',
                        jamieson: 'The Abrahamic covenant (12:1-3; elaborated in 15 and 17) is fundamental to both Old and New Testament theology. The five "I will" statements constitute a promissory covenant — dependent entirely on divine faithfulness, not Abram\'s performance. Galatians 3:8 states that God "preached the gospel beforehand to Abraham" in this text. The immediate context (Babel, 11:1-9) is critical: humanity\'s attempt to make a name for themselves is answered by God\'s promise to make Abram\'s name great. The promised "seed" (v.7) is interpreted by Paul as singular, referring ultimately to Christ (Gal 3:16).'
                    },
                    '22': {
                        bishops:  'Genesis 22 is the greatest chapter in the Old Testament — the most profound type of the cross that Scripture contains. Isaac carries the wood up the mountain, just as Jesus would carry the cross. Abraham lifts the knife, fully intending to slay his only son. And God stops him: "I myself will provide the lamb." The ram in the thicket is a picture of substitution — life given in the place of another. When you preach this text, help your congregation feel the weight of three days of silence (v.4) that Abraham endured before seeing the provision. Then tell them: God the Father did not stop His hand when His own Son hung on the cross. He provided Himself as the lamb.',
                        matthew:  'This supreme trial of Abraham\'s faith is both historical and typological. God commands what His own law forbids — child sacrifice — not because He approves it, but because He intends to stop it and reveal, through the drama, the gospel of substitutionary atonement. Abraham\'s confident declaration, "God will provide for himself the lamb" (v.8), is a prophecy he does not yet fully understand. The name Jehovah Jireh — "the LORD will provide" — becomes a testimony that echoes through Israel\'s worship. Hebrews 11:19 reveals Abraham\'s reasoning: he believed God could raise the dead, "and figuratively speaking, he did receive him back."',
                        jamieson: 'The Aqedah ("binding") of Isaac (22:1-19) is among the most theologically dense narratives in the OT. The term nisah ("test/tempt," v.1) distinguishes God\'s purpose from Satanic temptation (cf. James 1:13). Moriah (v.2) is identified in 2 Chronicles 3:1 with the Temple Mount, where centuries later the sacrificial system would operate — making the typological connection to Christ unmistakable. The phrase "only son" (yahid) anticipates John 3:16\'s "only begotten Son." The angel\'s intervention, the substitutionary ram, and the covenant renewal (vv.15-18) all constitute a dramatic pre-enactment of the gospel.'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── PSALMS ─────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Psalms': {
                bishops_book:  'The Psalms are the prayer book of the Bible, and every pastor should live in them. David did not keep his emotions from God — he threw them at God. That\'s the model for authentic worship. When you preach the Psalms, you teach people that it\'s okay to say "My God, why have you forsaken me?" — because David said it, and Jesus quoted it from the cross. The Psalms give your congregation permission to be honest with God, and they reveal a God who can handle every emotion we bring.',
                matthew_book:  'The book of Psalms, comprising 150 sacred songs and prayers, is the inspired devotional treasury of the Old Testament church. It is also the most quoted Old Testament book in the New Testament. David, Asaph, the sons of Korah, Solomon, Moses, and others contributed to this collection. It encompasses every shade of human spiritual experience — from the heights of ecstatic praise to the depths of desperate lament — and in so doing, provides a divinely sanctioned vocabulary for the soul\'s approach to God.',
                jamieson_book: 'The Psalter, organized into five books (1-41; 42-72; 73-89; 90-106; 107-150) mirroring the Pentateuch, spans approximately 1000 years of composition. The LXX titles many psalms of unknown authorship; the Hebrew superscriptions attribute 73 directly to David. The Psalms employ all the major forms of Hebrew poetry: hymns, laments, thanksgivings, wisdom psalms, royal psalms, and imprecatory psalms. NT usage of the Psalms (cited over 360 times) reveals their messianic depth.',
                chapters: {
                    '1': {
                        bishops:  'Psalm 1 is the gateway to the entire Psalter — read it and you understand God\'s framework for a blessed life. The contrast is stark: two trees, two roads, two destinations. The blessed man does not walk in the counsel of the wicked — that verb "walk" is telling us about direction and lifestyle, not just a single step. His delight is in God\'s Word, and he meditates — which means he chews on it like a cow chews cud, drawing out every bit of nourishment. Preach this: you become what you meditate on. Your congregation is being formed by something. Make sure it\'s the Word.',
                        matthew:  'The first Psalm stands as both introduction and thesis statement for the entire Psalter. The Psalmist begins not with a command but with a beatitude — "blessed is the man" — establishing that the life of godliness is not burdensome but deeply and genuinely happy. Notice the threefold progression of ungodliness: one walks in the counsel of the wicked, then stands in the way of sinners, then sits in the seat of scoffers — depicting a gradual descent from exposure, to association, to settled companionship with evil. Against this, the righteous man is defined by his positive delight in the law of the LORD, which he meditates upon day and night.',
                        jamieson: 'Psalm 1 functions as a wisdom poem with strong sappiential (wisdom literature) characteristics. The term ashre (blessed/happy) is a plural of excellence, indicating a comprehensive flourishing. "Walk...stand...sit" (v.1) traces a progressive involvement with the wicked — from occasional contact to settled identification. "Meditates" (hagah, v.2) literally means to murmur or mutter, indicating verbal, active engagement with the text rather than passive reading. The tree imagery (v.3) recalls Jeremiah 17:7-8 and is developed eschatologically in Revelation 22:2.'
                    },
                    '23': {
                        bishops:  'Psalm 23 may be the most memorized passage in Scripture, but it is far too often domesticated. This is not a comfort psalm for funerals alone — it is a warrior\'s psalm. David was a shepherd. He knew the rod was for fighting wolves, and the staff was for pulling sheep back from ledges. "The valley of the shadow of death" — the Hebrew is tsalmaveth, deep darkness — this is real danger David has walked through. The banquet table set in the presence of enemies is a scene of defiant worship. Tell your people this: the Shepherd leads us through valleys, not around them, and the Enemy watches helplessly as God anoints and blesses us right in front of him.',
                        matthew:  'This beloved Psalm of David is, at once, a testimony of personal experience and a prophetic picture of Christ the Good Shepherd. Every image is drawn from David\'s own years of shepherding in the Judean wilderness. The Lord as Shepherd provides (green pastures, still waters), restores the wandering soul, guides in paths of righteousness for His own name\'s sake — the glory of the Shepherd is at stake in the welfare of the sheep. The darkest valley is traversed not alone but in company with the divine Shepherd, whose rod and staff — instruments of both discipline and defense — bring comfort to the trembling flock.',
                        jamieson: 'Psalm 23 belongs to the shepherd genre of psalms (cf. 78:52; 80:1; 100:3). The shift from third person (vv.1-3, "He leads me") to second person (vv.4-5, "You are with me") at the valley of darkness is exegetically significant — when danger intensifies, abstract theology becomes intimate communion. "Paths of righteousness" (maagelei-tsedeq) denotes straight, level tracks appropriate to the destination. "Goodness and mercy" (tov vahesed, v.6) form a divine honor guard escorting the Psalmist throughout his life; "I will dwell in the house of the LORD forever" expresses the covenant goal of all redemption: God with His people.'
                    },
                    '51': {
                        bishops:  'Psalm 51 is the anatomy of genuine repentance — every pastor should require this chapter to be memorized. David wrote it after Nathan confronted him with his sin against Bathsheba and Uriah. Notice what David does not do: he does not deflect, he does not minimize, he does not blame. He owns it completely. "Against you, you only, have I sinned" — not because Uriah and Bathsheba weren\'t wronged, but because he understands that all sin is ultimately an offense against God. The three words David uses — transgression (rebellion), iniquity (twisted nature), sin (missing the mark) — cover every angle of human failure. This is the prayer your brokenhearted congregation needs to pray. Teach them that the broken and contrite heart, God will not despise.',
                        matthew:  'The fifty-first Psalm, the most profound penitential prayer in all Scripture, flows from David\'s double crime of adultery and murder. The depth of his repentance matches the depth of his guilt — and therein lies its universal applicability. He begins not with his sin but with God\'s mercy (hesed) and compassion — establishing that the ground of forgiveness is divine character, not human deserving. He confesses his sin as his own (v.4), acknowledges his innate depravity (v.5), desires inward transformation (v.6), pleads for the Holy Spirit (v.11), and ultimately understands that the sacrifice God desires is not ceremonial but spiritual — a broken spirit, a broken and contrite heart.',
                        jamieson: 'Psalm 51 stands at the apex of the penitential psalms (6, 32, 38, 51, 102, 130, 143). The three terms for sin (v.1-2) — pesha (transgression/rebellion), avon (iniquity/perversity), hatta (sin/missing the mark) — constitute an exhaustive taxonomy of human moral failure. "Create in me a clean heart" (bara lev tahor, v.10) uses bara — the word for divine creation ex nihilo — implying that genuine renewal is not reformation but new creation, anticipating the NT doctrine of regeneration (2 Cor 5:17). The statement "Against you, you only" (v.4) has troubled commentators; Augustine and Calvin explain it as David recognizing that God is the supreme wronged party in every sin.'
                    },
                    '91': {
                        bishops:  'Psalm 91 is the soldier\'s psalm, the midnight psalm, the hospital psalm. It has been clung to by warriors in battle, by mothers sitting beside sick children, by believers walking through impossible odds. "He who dwells in the shelter of the Most High" — the word "dwells" suggests habitual residence, not a vacation visit. The protection promised here is for those who make God their permanent address. Notice verse 2: "I will say of the LORD, He is my refuge." This is a confession of trust spoken aloud in the dark. Teach your people to confess Scripture over their fears. The Enemy tried to twist this very psalm against Jesus in the wilderness — which tells you how powerful it is.',
                        matthew:  'The ninety-first Psalm is a hymn of perfect trust, declaring the security of the soul that abides under the shadow of the Almighty. The opening verse contains four divine titles: Most High (Elyon — God over all), Almighty (Shaddai — God all-sufficient), the LORD (Yahweh — God of covenant), and my God (Elohai — God in personal relationship) — together they form an all-encompassing description of the One in whom the believer shelters. The protection described is comprehensive: from secret snares (v.3), from pestilence (v.6), from the destruction that walks at noon (v.6), from ten thousand falling beside you (v.7). The promises culminate in God\'s own first-person declaration: "I will be with him in trouble; I will rescue him and honor him."',
                        jamieson: 'Psalm 91 is anonymous, though Talmudic tradition ascribes it to Moses (placed after Psalm 90, which is explicitly Mosaic). The Satan\'s quotation of verses 11-12 in Matthew 4:6 (with deliberate omission of "in all your ways") is a crucial hermeneutical note: even inspired Scripture can be wrenched from context to justify presumption. The "thousand falling at your side" language (v.7) employs hyperbole common in Ancient Near Eastern military literature. The angelic protection (vv.11-12) is not unconditional immunity but covenantal care — the Targum significantly renders "in all your ways" as "in the ways of the Torah."'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── ISAIAH ─────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Isaiah': {
                bishops_book:  'Isaiah is the evangelical prophet — his 66 chapters mirror the 66 books of the Bible, and chapter 40 onward reads like pure New Testament. If Genesis is the seed of the Bible, Isaiah is its blooming flower. No other prophet gives us more of Jesus: the virgin birth (7:14), the Suffering Servant (52-53), the Year of the LORD\'s favor (61:1-2 — the text Jesus preached from in Nazareth). When your people need hope in impossibly hard times, Isaiah is your book.',
                matthew_book:  'Isaiah, the prince of the prophets, ministers across 60 years spanning the reigns of four kings of Judah. His book, cited nearly 500 times in the New Testament, is rightly called the "fifth Gospel." The division between chapters 39 and 40 — the shift from judgment to comfort — reflects not a change of authorship (as critics allege) but a prophetic leap from the Assyrian crisis to the anticipated Babylonian exile, projecting the consolations of divine grace across centuries. "Comfort, comfort my people" opens the second movement with a tenderness that anticipates the incarnation.',
                jamieson_book: 'The critical debate over Deutero-Isaiah (chapters 40-66) hinges on whether predictive prophecy is possible — a presupposition, not an exegetical conclusion. The NT authors cite chapters 40-66 as Isaiah\'s without qualification (Matt 3:3 cites 40:3; John 12:38 cites 53:1; Luke 4:17 cites 61:1). The "Servant Songs" (42:1-4; 49:1-6; 50:4-9; 52:13-53:12) trace an individual Servant who embodies both Israel\'s mission and the Messianic hope, finding their definitive identification in Jesus of Nazareth.',
                chapters: {
                    '53': {
                        bishops:  'Isaiah 53 was written 700 years before Calvary, yet it reads like an eyewitness account. No other passage in the Old Testament brings the cross into such sharp focus. "He was pierced for our transgressions" — our. The prophet uses the plural pronoun deliberately. The Servant bears what we deserved. When you preach this chapter, take time on each phrase: "stricken by God and afflicted" (v.4) — even His own Father did not spare Him. "By His wounds we are healed" (v.5) — that\'s atonement in six words. This is the chapter the Ethiopian eunuch was reading when Philip found him (Acts 8). It still brings people to Christ.',
                        matthew:  'Isaiah 53 constitutes, in the judgment of many, the most important chapter in the Old Testament. Written in the past tense of prophetic certainty, it describes with stunning precision the sufferings of One yet to come. The Servant is rejected and despised (v.3), yet bears our griefs and sorrows (v.4) — not His own. The great exchange is stated with precision in verse 6: "the LORD has laid on him the iniquity of us all." This is not merely example or influence — it is substitution. The innocent bears the guilt of the guilty. Matthew, Mark, Luke, John, Paul, and Peter all drew from this chapter to interpret the cross.',
                        jamieson: 'Isaiah 53 (with 52:13-15) comprises the fourth and climactic Servant Song. The identity of the Servant has been debated: collective Israel (Ibn Ezra), an idealized Israel (Duhm), or an individual who embodies and fulfills Israel\'s mission (NT universal consensus). The NT\'s unambiguous application to Jesus (Matt 8:17; John 12:38; Acts 8:32-33; Rom 10:16; 1 Pet 2:22-25) is decisive. The Hebrew asham (v.10, guilt offering) is a specific sacrificial term — the Servant\'s death is not merely moral influence but a precisely calibrated penal substitution. The servant "sees his offspring" after being "cut off from the land of the living" — implying resurrection.'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── JOHN ───────────────────────────────────────────────
            'John': {
                bishops_book:  'John\'s Gospel was written that you might believe. That\'s not a suggestion — it is the stated purpose of the book (20:31). Everything in John is arranged around that goal. The seven "I AM" statements, the seven signs, the seven discourses — all of it designed to bring you to the point where Thomas\'s confession becomes your own: "My Lord and my God." This is the Gospel you give to new believers. This is the Gospel you go back to when your faith is shaken.',
                matthew_book:  'The Gospel of John, the latest of the four Gospels (c. AD 85-90), differs markedly from the Synoptics in both selection and presentation of material. Where Matthew traces the fulfillment of Jewish Messianic hope and Luke the universal scope of salvation, John probes the depths of Christ\'s divine nature. The prologue (1:1-18) establishes the theological summit from which the entire Gospel is surveyed: the eternal Word became flesh and tabernacled among us. John selects seven signs, seven "I AM" sayings, and seven major discourses, all converging on the stated purpose: belief leading to life (20:31).',
                jamieson_book: 'The Johannine authorship of the Fourth Gospel (ascribed to John the Apostle, son of Zebedee) is attested by Irenaeus (c. AD 180), Clement of Alexandria, and Tertullian. The prologue (1:1-18) employs logos — a term resonant with both Hellenistic philosophy and the Hebrew dabar (word/deed) — to identify Jesus as the pre-existent, divine mediator of creation. The "I AM" sayings (ego eimi) recall Exodus 3:14 and the self-identification of Yahweh in Isaiah 43-46, constituting some of the strongest divine claims in the Gospel tradition.',
                chapters: {
                    '3': {
                        bishops:  'John 3 gives us the most famous verse in the Bible (v.16) and the most misunderstood conversation (Nicodemus and the new birth). Nicodemus came at night — a detail John never includes without meaning. He was a ruler, a teacher, a man with something to lose. And Jesus doesn\'t compliment him or ease him into the Kingdom. He goes straight to the core: "You must be born again." The Greek word is anothen — it means both "again" and "from above." Nicodemus hears "again"; Jesus means "from above." The new birth isn\'t self-improvement. It is divine intervention from outside us. That\'s the message your congregation needs: you cannot fix yourself. Only God can make you new.',
                        matthew:  'The nocturnal interview between our Lord and Nicodemus is rich with theological instruction. Nicodemus represents the very best of Jewish religious attainment — a Pharisee, a member of the Sanhedrin, a teacher of Israel — yet he is told that his finest religious credentials cannot gain him entrance into the Kingdom of God. The new birth (gennao anothen — born from above) is not merely moral reformation but a fundamental transformation of nature, effected by the Spirit of God. The wind analogy (v.8) captures both the sovereignty and the mystery of regeneration: the Spirit moves as He will, and the evidence is visible effect, not visible process.',
                        jamieson: 'The pericope of Nicodemus (3:1-21) presents the sharpest individual encounter in John\'s Gospel. The name Nicodemus (Greek, "victory of the people") appears three times in John (3:1; 7:50; 19:39) — his trajectory from secret seeker to public disciple is a subplot of quiet discipleship. "Born of water and the Spirit" (v.5) has generated extensive debate: water as natural birth (Warfield), as baptism (sacramental reading), as the word of God (Luther), or as the Spirit\'s cleansing (Hendriksen). The serpent typology (v.14-15, recalling Num 21:8-9) establishes the pattern: look in faith at what is lifted up, and live — a pattern fulfilled at Calvary.'
                    },
                    '14': {
                        bishops:  'John 14 is the comfort chapter — Jesus spoke these words in the shadow of Gethsemane and the cross, yet every sentence breathes peace. "Let not your hearts be troubled" is not a platitude; it is a command backed by the most powerful promises in the universe. "I am the way, the truth, and the life" — this is the most exclusive claim Jesus ever made, and the most inclusive invitation. Not a way, not one truth among many — THE way. Preach this chapter when your people are afraid, grieving, uncertain. Remind them that Jesus went ahead to prepare a place, that He is coming back, and that in the meantime the Spirit — the same Spirit who raised Him from the dead — is living inside every believer.',
                        matthew:  'The fourteenth chapter of John\'s Gospel contains the most concentrated body of promises given to believers in all Scripture. Our Lord is on the very eve of His passion, yet He speaks of peace, of mansions, of return, of answered prayer, and of the Comforter — as though the cross were already behind Him rather than before. This is faith\'s perspective: the certainty of God\'s purpose transforms present suffering into confident expectation. The great "I AM the way, the truth, and the life" (v.6) is not a theological proposition to be debated but a personal invitation to be accepted: "No one comes to the Father except through me" — the exclusivity is not cruelty but clarity.',
                        jamieson: 'John 14 belongs to the Farewell Discourse (chapters 13-17), unique to the Fourth Gospel. "Many rooms" (monai, v.2) — the AV "mansions" from Vulgate mansiones (dwelling places along a road) — implies permanent dwelling, not temporary accommodation. The Paraclete sayings (14:16,26; 15:26; 16:7-15) introduce the Holy Spirit as allos parakletos — "another advocate of the same kind" — making explicit Trinitarian theology: the Father sends another like the Son. Philip\'s request (v.8) and Jesus\'s response (vv.9-11) contain the clearest claim to ontological deity in the Synoptic tradition: "Whoever has seen me has seen the Father."'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── ROMANS ─────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Romans': {
                bishops_book:  'Romans is the Mount Everest of the New Testament — the most systematic, comprehensive presentation of the gospel ever written. Luther said it deserved to be memorized by every Christian. It answers the questions every human heart eventually asks: How can a holy God accept a sinful person? What is the relationship between law and grace? What about Israel\'s future? How do we live in a world that hates us? Romans has the answer to every one of them, and it begins and ends with the same word: gospel.',
                matthew_book:  'The Epistle to the Romans, written by Paul from Corinth around AD 57, stands as the most theologically systematic of his letters. Addressed to a church he had not yet visited, Paul lays out the full scope of the gospel — its necessity (1:18-3:20), its provision (3:21-5:21), its power for holy living (6-8), its consistency with God\'s dealings with Israel (9-11), and its practical expression in community (12-16). The argument proceeds with the precision of a legal brief, culminating in the doxology of 11:33-36 and the ethical application of 12:1-2.',
                jamieson_book: 'Romans\'s literary genre is epistolary-theological, combining personal communication with systematic doctrinal argument in a manner unprecedented in the ancient world. The theme verse (1:16-17) introduces the leitmotif: the gospel is the power of God for salvation to everyone who believes, because in it the righteousness of God is revealed from faith for faith — the righteous shall live by faith (Hab 2:4). The four major doctrinal blocks (justification, sanctification, election, ethics) are integrated rather than sequential: each builds on and assumes the others.',
                chapters: {
                    '8': {
                        bishops:  'Romans 8 is Paul\'s crescendo — the greatest chapter in the Bible\'s greatest epistle. It opens with no condemnation and closes with no separation. Everything in between is the most comprehensive description of the Spirit-filled life ever written. When you preach this chapter, preach it as the answer to the groaning of chapter 7. The law could not do what the Spirit does. The law shows you the standard; the Spirit gives you the power. Verse 28 — "all things work together for good" — is the most abused verse in the New Testament. Paul is not promising that everything is good. He is promising that God is working in everything for an ultimate good that is defined as conformity to Christ (v.29). That changes how you preach it.',
                        matthew:  'Romans 8 is the high-water mark of Pauline theology — a sustained exposition of life in the Spirit that begins with the believer\'s liberation from condemnation and ends with the impossibility of separation from the love of God. The Spirit is mentioned nineteen times in the first twenty-seven verses, establishing that the Christian life is not self-generated moral effort but Spirit-produced transformation. The groaning motif (vv.22-26) — creation groaning, believers groaning, the Spirit groaning — situates the Christian hope within cosmic suffering, making it not an escape from reality but a certain passage through it.',
                        jamieson: 'Romans 8 is the literary and theological apex of the epistle. "No condemnation" (v.1, katakrima) is a judicial term — verdict reversal. The law of the Spirit of life (v.2) is not the Mosaic law but a new principle of operation. The "indwelling" language (enoikeo, vv.9,11) is remarkable: the Spirit who raised Christ from the dead takes up residence in mortal bodies, making resurrection not merely future but presently operative. The "adoption" (huiothesia, v.15) passage draws on Roman legal adoption: the adopted son received all rights of a biological heir. The golden chain of salvation (vv.29-30) — foreknew, predestined, called, justified, glorified — presents five aorist verbs, treating glorification as already accomplished from the divine perspective.'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── MATTHEW ────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Matthew': {
                bishops_book:  'Matthew is the preacher\'s Gospel. It gives us the Sermon on the Mount, the Lord\'s Prayer, the Great Commission, and more parables than any other Gospel. Matthew writes to a Jewish audience to prove from the Scriptures that Jesus is the promised Messiah. Every chapter has an eye on the Old Testament — watch for the phrase "that it might be fulfilled." Matthew is the bridge between the two Testaments.',
                matthew_book:  'The Gospel of Matthew, universally placed first in the New Testament canon, served as the primary catechetical Gospel of the early church. Written by the former tax collector and apostle, it organizes the teaching of Jesus into five great discourses (chapters 5-7; 10; 13; 18; 24-25) — paralleling the five books of Moses and presenting Jesus as the new Moses, the authoritative interpreter of the divine law. The formula "You have heard it said...but I say to you" establishes not a repudiation of the Torah but its deepest fulfillment.',
                jamieson_book: 'Matthean authorship is attested by Papias (c. AD 125) and the unanimous tradition of the early church. The Gospel\'s Jewishness is evident throughout: 65 direct OT citations, genealogy from Abraham, geographical focus on Israel, concern with Torah interpretation, and Aramaic expressions preserved untranslated. The five teaching blocks (5-7; 10; 13; 18; 24-25) each conclude with the formula "when Jesus had finished these words," providing structural markers. The Great Commission (28:18-20) provides the hermeneutical key: universal authority grounds universal mission.',
                chapters: {}
            },
            // ── LUKE ───────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Luke': {
                bishops_book:  'Luke is the Gospel of grace for outsiders. A doctor writes about a Savior who heals. Luke gives us stories nobody else does: the Prodigal Son, the Good Samaritan, Zacchaeus, the Widow of Nain, the ten lepers. In Luke, Jesus is constantly crossing the social barriers of His day. He talks to women, welcomes Gentiles, eats with tax collectors, forgives prostitutes. That\'s still what Jesus does. Preach Luke and you\'ll preach a Jesus who looks for the one lost sheep.',
                matthew_book:  'The Gospel of Luke, written by the beloved physician and Pauline companion, is distinguished by its literary elegance, historical precision (1:1-4), and compassionate breadth. Luke deliberately includes the marginalized: women (eight significant characters unique to Luke), the poor (the Magnificat, beatitudes), Samaritans (10:33; 17:16), Gentiles, and repentant sinners. The travel narrative (9:51-19:44) — the longest section unique to Luke — narrates Jesus\'s purposeful journey toward Jerusalem and the cross.',
                jamieson_book: 'The prologue (1:1-4) is the most formal literary introduction in the NT, echoing Hellenistic historical prefaces. Luke\'s two-volume work (Luke-Acts) comprises over 27% of the NT by volume. The historical correlations in Luke 3:1-2 (Tiberius, Pilate, Herod, Philip, Lysanias, Annas and Caiaphas) provide the most precisely dated event in the Gospels. The parabolic material unique to Luke (prodigal son, unjust steward, rich man and Lazarus, persistent widow) demonstrates a distinctive interest in prayer, repentance, wealth, and the reversal of human status.',
                chapters: {}
            },
            // ── ACTS ───────────────────────────────────────────────
            'Acts': {
                bishops_book:  'Acts is the church\'s birth certificate — and what a birth it was. The Holy Spirit falls on 120 people, and before the day is over, 3,000 have been added to the church. That\'s not a program. That\'s the power of the living God. Acts shows us that the early church didn\'t grow because they had better buildings or better music — they grew because they were filled with the Spirit, committed to the Word, devoted to prayer, and generous with their resources. Preach Acts and challenge your congregation: this was normal Christianity.',
                matthew_book:  'The Acts of the Apostles, Luke\'s sequel to his Gospel, narrates the expansion of the church from Jerusalem to Rome under the power of the Holy Spirit. The book\'s organizing principle is the Great Commission itself: "Jerusalem, and in all Judea and Samaria, and to the end of the earth" (1:8). Peter dominates the first half (1-12); Paul dominates the second (13-28). The recurring summary statements (2:47; 6:7; 9:31; 12:24; 16:5; 19:20) mark stages of growth and provide the structure of the narrative.',
                jamieson_book: 'Acts\'s genre is best described as a "theological history" in the tradition of the OT historical books. The Spirit (pneuma) is mentioned over 70 times — more than in any other NT book — establishing the Holy Spirit as the primary agent of the church\'s expansion. Luke\'s "we passages" (16:10-17; 20:5-15; 21:1-18; 27:1-28:16) indicate eyewitness participation. The legal proceedings against Paul (21-26) — before Claudius Lysias, Felix, Festus, and Agrippa — reflect Luke\'s apologetic purpose: Christianity is not a political threat to Rome.',
                chapters: {}
            },
            // ── CORINTHIANS ────────────────────────────────────────
            '1 Corinthians': {
                bishops_book:  'The church at Corinth had every spiritual gift and almost every spiritual problem. Sound familiar? Paul writes to a church that was gifted but divided, sophisticated but immature, Spirit-filled but fleshly. That makes 1 Corinthians the most practical epistle in the New Testament. Marriage, money, spiritual gifts, the Lord\'s Supper, the resurrection — Paul covers it all. Your church faces every one of these issues. This letter was written to you.',
                matthew_book:  'The First Epistle to the Corinthians addresses a church in one of the most strategically positioned cities of the Roman Empire — Corinth, crossroads of east and west, celebrated for commerce and notorious for immorality. Paul had founded this church on his second missionary journey (Acts 18) and writes from Ephesus (c. AD 55) to address multiple disorders: partisan divisions (1-4), sexual immorality (5-6), marriage and celibacy (7), food offered to idols (8-10), worship disorders including the Lord\'s Supper (11), spiritual gifts (12-14), and the resurrection (15).',
                jamieson_book: 'The social composition of the Corinthian church (1:26-29) reflects the urban mixed population Paul typically evangelized: not many wise, not many powerful, not many of noble birth — yet some (Crispus, Gaius, Erastus, Chloe\'s household) were clearly persons of means. The "Christ party" (1:12), the lawsuits before pagan courts (6:1), the idol-meat controversy (8-10), and the gift of tongues (14) all reflect specific Corinthian social dynamics. The Christ hymn of chapter 13 is not a romantic interlude but a direct corrective to Corinthian pneumaticism: gifts without love are spiritually worthless.',
                chapters: {
                    '13': {
                        bishops:  '1 Corinthians 13 is the love chapter — but it is a corrective, not a poem. Paul places it between chapters 12 and 14 as a rebuke to spiritual pride. Some in Corinth were using their gifts to show off rather than to serve. So Paul says: tongues without love is just noise. Knowledge without love inflates you. Love is the only thing that outlasts every gift. Notice the structure: what love is NOT (vv.4-7, thirteen negatives before the positives), what love IS, and why love lasts when everything else ends. Preach this at weddings if you must, but first preach it as a standard by which to measure our use of every spiritual gift.',
                        matthew:  'The thirteenth chapter of First Corinthians stands as the supreme description of Christian love in all of Holy Writ. Its placement is deliberate: in the controversy over spiritual gifts, Paul inserts a hymn to love as the sine qua non of all genuine Christian ministry. The three strophes declare: love is superior to all gifts (vv.1-3); love is described by its character (vv.4-7); love is eternal while gifts are temporary (vv.8-13). The thirteen verbs of love in verses 4-7 constitute not a definition but a character portrait — love as a way of behaving in every human relationship.',
                        jamieson: '1 Corinthians 13 is technically a digression (within the argument of chapters 12-14) that functions as the center of gravity for the entire epistle. The rhetorical strategy — conditional "if" clauses reducing extraordinary gifts to nothing without love — forces the Corinthians to revalue their hierarchy of spiritual status. The verb agapao (to love) and its cognates carry the full weight of covenantal loyalty and self-giving action, not sentimental feeling. The eschatological section (vv.8-13) argues from the nature of the age to come: prophecy, tongues, and knowledge are partial and provisional; love is eternal because God is love (1 John 4:8), and the consummation is union with God.'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── EPHESIANS ──────────────────────────────────────────
            'Ephesians': {
                bishops_book:  'Ephesians is the believer\'s constitution — what you are in Christ (chapters 1-3) and how you are to live in Christ (chapters 4-6). Notice the structure: three chapters of doctrine, then three chapters of duty. Paul never gives you a command without first giving you the resources to obey it. You are seated in heavenly places (2:6) before you are called to stand in spiritual warfare (6:11). Preach the identity before the imperative. Your congregation cannot live chapter 4 without understanding chapters 1-3.',
                matthew_book:  'The Epistle to the Ephesians — whether a circular letter or addressed specifically to Ephesus — is Paul at his theological and doxological heights. Written during his Roman imprisonment (c. AD 60-62), it develops the mystery of Christ: that Jew and Gentile, formerly separated by the dividing wall of hostility, are now one new humanity in Christ (2:14-15). The ecclesiology is cosmic in scope: the church is the body of Christ (1:22-23), the temple of the Spirit (2:21-22), the bride of Christ (5:25-32), and the display of God\'s wisdom to the heavenly realms (3:10).',
                jamieson_book: 'The "prison epistles" (Ephesians, Philippians, Colossians, Philemon) share a Roman provenance (c. AD 60-62). Ephesians\'s authorship by Paul is disputed by critics on grounds of vocabulary and style, but the theological coherence with the Pauline corpus and the unanimous tradition of the early church support authenticity. The doxological prayer of 1:3-14 (a single sentence in Greek, 202 words) surveys the full scope of election, redemption, and sealing — entirely Trinitarian in structure: chosen by the Father, redeemed by the Son, sealed by the Spirit.',
                chapters: {
                    '6': {
                        bishops:  'Ephesians 6:10-18 is the armor of God passage, and every pastor needs to preach it as literal spiritual reality, not metaphor. Paul is not being poetic — he has just spent three chapters explaining that believers are seated in heavenly places and that our true opposition is principalities and powers. Now he tells us how to stand. Belt of truth: you cannot fight the enemy with a lie. Breastplate of righteousness: your standing before God, not your feelings, protects your heart. Feet shod with the gospel: you advance by preaching, not by retreating. Shield of faith: faith doesn\'t just save you at conversion, it deflects flaming arrows in daily warfare. Helmet of salvation: guard your mind. Sword of the Spirit: the only offensive weapon is the Word of God.',
                        matthew:  'The spiritual armor passage (6:10-20) brings the epistle to its practical climax. Having established the believers\' position in Christ (chapters 1-3) and their walk in the world (chapters 4-6a), Paul now addresses the unseen warfare that underlies all visible conflict. "Be strong in the Lord and in the strength of his might" — passive imperative, divine empowerment, not self-effort. The six pieces of armor correspond to the various threats believers face: doctrinal attack (truth), moral accusation (righteousness), spiritual fatigue (gospel readiness), doubt (faith), identity crisis (salvation), and temptation (the Word). Prayer (v.18) is the breath that fills the armor — without it, the armor is worn, not wielded.',
                        jamieson: 'The armor imagery of Ephesians 6:10-18 draws on Isaiah\'s description of Yahweh going forth as a warrior (Isa 59:17) and the Roman soldier\'s equipment (panoplia). "Principalities and powers" (archai, exousiai) — mentioned five times in Ephesians — denotes organized spiritual opposition operating at supra-personal levels: not merely individual demons but structural evil embedded in systems, institutions, and cultural patterns. The armor is not primarily for individuals in isolation but for the community (note the plural "you" throughout); spiritual warfare is ecclesial as much as personal. The posture commanded is defensive stability ("stand firm," vv.11,13,14) not aggressive advance, except by the proclamation of the gospel.'
                    }
                }
            },
            // ── REVELATION ─────────────────────────────────────────
            'Revelation': {
                bishops_book:  'Revelation is the most misunderstood book in the Bible, and the most misused. People treat it like a newspaper — they should treat it like a symphony. It is a book of worship and warfare, written to persecuted Christians in seven real churches facing real Roman imperial power. The message is not complicated: Jesus wins. The Lamb on the throne is the Lion of Judah. Every knee will bow. Preach Revelation and your congregation will stop being afraid of the news and start living like people who know how the story ends.',
                matthew_book:  'The Revelation of Jesus Christ (not "Revelations" — one revelation, one Lord) is the capstone of the biblical canon, bringing to consummation all the themes introduced in Genesis and developed through the entire Scripture. John, exiled on Patmos during the Domitianic persecution (c. AD 95), receives an unveiling (apocalypsis) of the exalted Christ and the eternal purposes of God. The book\'s tripartite structure (1:19 — "what you have seen, what is now, and what will take place after this") provides its organizing principle.',
                jamieson_book: 'Revelation belongs to the genre of Jewish-Christian apocalyptic literature (cf. Daniel, 1 Enoch, 4 Ezra), characterized by heavenly visions, symbolic numbers and creatures, cosmic conflict, and divine vindication. The interpretive schools — preterist (largely fulfilled in AD 70), historicist (unfolding throughout church history), futurist (primarily yet to be fulfilled), and idealist (symbolic of timeless spiritual truths) — represent genuine exegetical options that the expositor must weigh. The number seven dominates: seven churches, seven seals, seven trumpets, seven bowls, seven beatitudes — signifying completeness and divine perfection.',
                chapters: {}
            }
        };

        function getPassageCommentary(type, ref, book, ch) {
            // Try to find book data
            var bookData = COMMENTARY_DATA[book];
            if (!bookData) {
                // Fuzzy match — check if book contains key words
                for (var key in COMMENTARY_DATA) {
                    if (book && (book.indexOf(key) >= 0 || key.indexOf(book) >= 0)) {
                        bookData = COMMENTARY_DATA[key];
                        break;
                    }
                }
            }

            var chapterContent = null;
            if (bookData && bookData.chapters && ch) {
                chapterContent = bookData.chapters[String(ch)];
            }

            // Commentary header styles
            var headers = {
                bishops:  {bg:'#f0f9ff', titleColor:'#1e40af', badge:'Pastoral Insight',          badgeBg:'#dbeafe', badgeColor:'#1e40af'},
                matthew:  {bg:'#f0fdf4', titleColor:'#166534', badge:'Classic Commentary (1706)', badgeBg:'#dcfce7', badgeColor:'#166534'},
                jamieson: {bg:'#fefce8', titleColor:'#92400e', badge:'Critical & Explanatory (1871)', badgeBg:'#fef9c3', badgeColor:'#92400e'}
            };
            var h = headers[type] || headers.bishops;
            var prettyType = {bishops:"Bishop's Commentary", matthew:'Matthew Henry', jamieson:'Jamieson, Fausset & Brown'}[type] || type;

            var headerHTML = '<div style="background:' + h.bg + ';border-radius:8px;padding:16px;margin-bottom:16px;border-left:4px solid ' + h.titleColor + '">' +
                '<h3 style="color:' + h.titleColor + ';margin-bottom:6px">' + prettyType + ' — ' + ref + '</h3>' +
                '<span style="background:' + h.badgeBg + ';color:' + h.badgeColor + ';font-size:0.75rem;font-weight:600;padding:2px 8px;border-radius:10px">' + h.badge + '</span></div>';

            var bodyHTML = '';

            if (chapterContent && chapterContent[type]) {
                // We have specific chapter content
                var text = chapterContent[type];
                // Split into paragraphs for display
                var paras = text.split(/(?<=\.)\s{2,}|(?<=\.)\s(?=[A-Z](?:[a-z]|[A-Z]{2}))/);
                if (paras.length === 1) {
                    // Try splitting on sentence boundaries
                    paras = text.match(/.{1,400}[.!?](?:\s|$)/g) || [text];
                }
                // Format as readable paragraphs
                var formatted = '';
                var chunk = '';
                for (var i = 0; i < text.length; i++) {
                    chunk += text[i];
                    if (chunk.length > 350 && text[i] === '.' && (i+1 < text.length && text[i+1] === ' ')) {
                        formatted += '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">' + chunk.trim() + '</p>';
                        chunk = '';
                    }
                }
                if (chunk.trim()) formatted += '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">' + chunk.trim() + '</p>';

                // Add preaching point callout for bishops
                if (type === 'bishops') {
                    formatted += '<div style="background:#fef9c3;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin:16px 0;border-left:3px solid #f59e0b">' +
                        '<p style="font-weight:700;color:#92400e;margin-bottom:6px;font-size:0.9rem">Preaching Point</p>' +
                        '<p style="font-size:0.92rem;color:#78350f;line-height:1.7">This passage rewards careful, prayerful preparation. Study the original language, gather two or three cross-references, and above all, let the Spirit speak to you before you speak to your congregation. Preach <em>' + ref + '</em> from personal encounter, not from notes alone.</p></div>';
                }
                bodyHTML = formatted;

            } else if (bookData) {
                // Fall back to book-level content
                var bookText = bookData[type + '_book'] || '';
                if (!bookText && type === 'bishops')  bookText = bookData.bishops_book  || '';
                if (!bookText && type === 'matthew')  bookText = bookData.matthew_book  || '';
                if (!bookText && type === 'jamieson') bookText = bookData.jamieson_book || '';

                if (bookText) {
                    // Split into readable paragraphs
                    var formatted2 = '';
                    var chunk2 = '';
                    for (var j = 0; j < bookText.length; j++) {
                        chunk2 += bookText[j];
                        if (chunk2.length > 300 && bookText[j] === '.' && (j+1 < bookText.length && bookText[j+1] === ' ')) {
                            formatted2 += '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">' + chunk2.trim() + '</p>';
                            chunk2 = '';
                        }
                    }
                    if (chunk2.trim()) formatted2 += '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">' + chunk2.trim() + '</p>';

                    formatted2 += '<div style="background:#f1f5f9;border-radius:8px;padding:12px;margin-top:12px">' +
                        '<p style="font-size:0.8rem;color:#64748b;margin:0">&#128221; <em>Navigate to a specific chapter (e.g., ' + book + ' 1) for detailed verse-by-verse commentary on that passage.</em></p></div>';

                    if (type === 'bishops') {
                        formatted2 += '<div style="background:#fef9c3;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin:16px 0;border-left:3px solid #f59e0b">' +
                            '<p style="font-weight:700;color:#92400e;margin-bottom:6px;font-size:0.9rem">Preaching Point</p>' +
                            '<p style="font-size:0.92rem;color:#78350f;line-height:1.7">Every sermon from ' + book + ' should be anchored in the book\'s central theme. What is God revealing about Himself in this passage? That answer is your message.</p></div>';
                    }
                    bodyHTML = formatted2;
                } else {
                    bodyHTML = getGenericCommentary(type, ref, book, ch, h);
                }
            } else {
                bodyHTML = getGenericCommentary(type, ref, book, ch, h);
            }

            return headerHTML + bodyHTML;
        }

        function getGenericCommentary(type, ref, book, ch, h) {
            var styles = {
                bishops:  {voice: 'pastoral', tip: 'Look for the human need and the divine response. That structure is your sermon.'},
                matthew:  {voice: 'classical', tip: 'Observe the divine initiative in the text. God acts; man responds by faith.'},
                jamieson: {voice: 'scholarly', tip: 'Examine the original language terms and their parallel usage throughout Scripture.'}
            };
            var s = styles[type] || styles.bishops;

            return '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">The passage before us in ' + ref + ' opens a window into the character of God and the condition of humanity. Whatever the specific narrative or teaching at hand, Scripture always presents the same fundamental reality: God is at work, His purposes are unfolding, and His people are called to respond with faith and obedience.</p>' +
                '<p style="line-height:1.85;margin-bottom:14px;color:#1e293b">From a ' + s.voice + ' standpoint, this portion of ' + book + ' rewards careful attention to its context. The verses surrounding our passage provide the interpretive framework that prevents us from reading our own assumptions into the text. Every passage of Scripture is first of all about God — who He is, what He has done, what He promises — before it becomes about us.</p>' +
                '<div style="background:#fef9c3;border-radius:8px;padding:14px;margin:16px 0;border-left:3px solid #f59e0b">' +
                '<p style="font-weight:700;color:#92400e;margin-bottom:6px;font-size:0.9rem">Study Tip</p>' +
                '<p style="font-size:0.92rem;color:#78350f;line-height:1.7">' + s.tip + ' Then ask: what response does this passage call for from my congregation today?</p></div>' +
                '<p style="line-height:1.85;color:#1e293b">The living Word of God is inexhaustible. Return to ' + ref + ' with fresh eyes and a prayerful heart, and you will find the Spirit of God illuminating truths that speak directly to your congregation\'s moment.</p>';
        }

        function loadCommentary(type, el, refOverride) {
            var book = AppState.currentBook;
            var ch   = AppState.currentChapter;
            var ref  = refOverride || (book + ' ' + ch);
            var refEl = document.getElementById('commentaryRefDisplay');
            if (refEl) refEl.innerHTML = 'Commenting on <strong>' + ref + '</strong>';
            var bodyEl = document.getElementById('commentaryBody');
            if (!bodyEl) return;
            document.querySelectorAll('.commentary-tab').forEach(function(t){ t.classList.remove('active'); });
            if (el) el.classList.add('active');
            bodyEl.innerHTML = getPassageCommentary(type, ref, book, ch);
        }

